e, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1420–24 July 1511":"1420–24 July 1511","1420–1511":"1420–1511","1422–Male":"1422–Deceased","1427–1499":"1427–1499","1448–1501":"1448–1501","1472–Female":"1472–Deceased","1479–Male":"1479–Deceased","1400–1449":"1400–1449","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","liv 1477":"1477","Abt 1479":"about 1479","after 24 July 1511":"after 24 July 1511","1448":"1448","1447":"1447","1501":"1501","1479":"1479","1511":"1511","1499":"1499","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","24 July 1511":"24 July 1511","1420":"1420","1449":"1449","1416":"1416","1427":"1427","Normanton, Yorkshire, England":"Normanton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England":"Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leavitt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>leuet</i> ‘wolf cub’ (see   Low   3).","habitational name from any of various places in Normandy called Livet. All are of obscure, presumably Gaulish, etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Low","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived near a tumulus, mound or hill, Middle English <i>lowe</i>, from Old English <i>hlāw</i> (see   Law   2).","Scottish and English: nickname for a short man, from Middle English <i>lah</i>, <i>lowe</i> (Old Norse <i>lágr</i>; the word was adopted first into the northern dialects of Middle English, where Scandinavian influence was strong, and then spread south, with regular alteration of the vowel quality).","English and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for a violent or dangerous person, from Anglo-Norman French <i>lou</i>, <i>leu</i> ‘wolf’ (from Latin <i>lupus</i>). Wolves were relatively common in Britain at the time when most surnames were formed, as there still existed large tracts of uncleared forest."]},{"name":"Levitt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Isador, Isadore, Ari, Batya, Hersh, Mayer, Meyer, Rina.","English: variant of   Leavitt  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Levit  ."]},{"name":"Levett","meanings":["English: variant of   Leavitt  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Leavitt III was born in 1420, in Normanton, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Leavett II, was 21 and his mother, Martha Elizabeth Ade, was 20. He married Elizabeth Syward in 1447, in Normanton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 24 July 1511, in Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 91, and was